04504nam a22005655i 9780822392798DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223927987 a10.1515/97808223927982doi  a(DE-B1597)554149  a(OCoLC)1243310349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF1376b.E377 2010 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a972/.652221 aEiss, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Name of El Pueblo :bPlace, Community, and the Politics of History in Yucatán /cPaul Eiss; ed. by Walter D. Mignolo, Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (354 p.) :b33 photographs, 3 maps, 6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations : 4600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction FROM ARCHIVE TO ASHES -- tI DISPOSSESSION -- tOne THE LAST CACIQUE -- tTwo King of the Forest -- tThree HUNUCMA’S ZAPATA -- tII REPOSSESSION -- tFour THE REDEMPTION -- tFive The General and the Beast -- tSix The President ’s Dead Hand -- tIII RECOGNITION -- tSeven The War of the Eggs -- tEight By the Virgin’s Grace -- tNine Poet, Prophet and Politician -- tConclusion “No”-Place -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe term “el pueblo” is used throughout Latin America, referring alternately to small towns, to community, or to “the people” as a political entity. In this vivid anthropological and historical analysis of Mexico’s Yucatán peninsula, Paul K. Eiss explores the multiple meanings of el pueblo and the power of the concept to unite the diverse claims made in its name. Eiss focuses on working-class indigenous and mestizo populations, examining how those groups negotiated the meaning of el pueblo among themselves and in their interactions with outsiders, including landowners, activists, and government officials. Combining extensive archival and ethnographic research, he describes how residents of the region have laid claim to el pueblo in varied ways, as exemplified in communal narratives recorded in archival documents, in the performance of plays and religious processions, and in struggles over land, politics, and the built environment. Eiss demonstrates that while el pueblo is used throughout the hemisphere, the term is given meaning and power through the ways it is imagined and constructed in local contexts. Moreover, he reveals el pueblo to be a concept that is as historical as it is political. It is in the name of el pueblo—rather than class, race, or nation—that inhabitants of northwestern Yucatán stake their deepest claims not only to social or political rights, but over history itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392798zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822392798/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles